06359nam a22008895i 9781503612884DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019051238  a97815036128847 a10.1515/97815036128842doi  a(DE-B1597)564560  a(OCoLC)1142936000  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHN79.A17bW67 2020 4aHN79.A17 7aHIS0361402bisacsh04a307.1/412097822300aWorld War II and the West It Wrought /ced. by David M. Kennedy, Mark Brilliant. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. EXECUTIVE DOMAIN -- t2. ENLISTING THE LABORATORIES -- t3. WORLD WAR II, THE COLD WAR, AND THE KNOWLEDGE ECONOMIES OF THE PACIFIC COAST -- t4. THE POLITICS WROUGHT BY WAR -- t5. THE ROOTS OF HISPANIC CONSERVATISM IN THE WARTIME WEST -- t6. “NO PRIVATE SCHOOL COULD EVER BE AS SATISFACTORY” -- t7. HOW THE PACIFIC WORLD BECAME WEST -- tAFTERWORD -- tNOTES -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew episodes in American history were more transformative than World War II, and in no region did it bring greater change than in the West. Having lifted the United States out of the Great Depression, World War II set in motion a massive westward population movement, ignited a quarter-century boom that redefined the West as the nation's most economically dynamic region, and triggered unprecedented public investment in manufacturing, education, scientific research, and infrastructure—an economic revolution that would lay the groundwork for prodigiously innovative high-tech centers in Silicon Valley, the Puget Sound area, and elsewhere. Amidst robust economic growth and widely shared prosperity in the post-war decades, Westerners made significant strides toward greater racial and gender equality, even as they struggled to manage the environmental consequences of their region's surging vitality. At the same time, wartime policies that facilitated the federal withdrawal of Western public lands and the occupation of Pacific islands for military use continued an ongoing project of U.S. expansionism at home and abroad. This volume explores the lasting consequences of a pivotal chapter in U.S. history, and offers new categories for understanding the post-war West. Contributors to this volume include Mark Brilliant, Geraldo L. Cadava, Matthew Dallek, Mary L. Dudziak, Jared Farmer, David M. Kennedy, Daniel J. Kevles, Rebecca Jo Plant, Gavin Wright, and Richard White.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPolitical culturezWest (U.S.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial changezWest (U.S.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xInfluence. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszWest (U.S.) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xSocial aspectszWest (U.S.). 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zWest (U.S.) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945zWest (U.S.). 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / West (AK, CA, CO, HI, ID, MT, NV, UT, WY).2bisacsh  aAmerican West.  aU.S. West.  aWorld War II - Economic aspects - West (U.S.).  aWorld War II - Political aspects - West (U.S.).  aWorld War II - Social aspects - West (U.S.).  aWorld War II.1 aBrilliant, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrilliant, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCadava, Geraldo L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDallek, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDudziak, Mary L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarmer, Jared, econtrib